Abstract

Improving health outcomes in diverse communities is contingent upon increasing representation in the complete research processes from data collection to analysis. While there are several barriers to conducting or participating in research for underrepresented groups, certain methods, such as community-based participatory research (CBPR), present solutions to celebrate and support creative collaboration towards progress. The University of Houston Community Health Worker Initiative (CHWI) complements the goals of CBPR by utilizing a data-guided approach to inform responsive engagement. I analyzed mixed-methods CHWI data from a sample of 123 respondents to explore potential interventions that could appropriately, effectively, and positively impact the community. The results of this analysis suggest that alluvial diagrams are a powerful method for visualizing categorical data to understand the relationships between variables in an exploratory fashion. While there are sample size limitations to this data, future work will attempt to better identify specific and implementable interventions to serve this community.

Methods

123 respondents from Houston Communities

Mixed-methods:

  • Quantitative demographic data
  • Qualitative interview data
    • Problems/barriers
    • Health concerns
    • Ways that a CHW could help the individual or their family

Categorization of the qualitative data was undertaken by the research team. The project manager of CHWI provided an initial set of categories based on experience from working with CHWs. Data was coded by two research assistants. Categories were iteratively revised based on collaboration by the project team.

Preparing the Data

I import the data, set the missing values, recode an additional education column from 5 to 4 values, and label the variables as factors.

Collapsing <MS & <HS for reducing noise in the alluvial diagrams because there are only 5 individuals in the <MS category. The sample demographics summary table and bar plots do not represent education as collapsed.

#import data
chw_stories <- read_csv("dat.csv")
#set 9 to NA, how it was manually coded
chw_stories[chw_stories==9] <- NA
#collapse edu for alluvial aesthetics (<MS & <HS collapsed)
chw_stories$edu_4[chw_stories$edu_5 ==0] = 0
chw_stories$edu_4[chw_stories$edu_5 ==1] = 0
chw_stories$edu_4[chw_stories$edu_5 ==2] = 1
chw_stories$edu_4[chw_stories$edu_5 ==3] = 2
chw_stories$edu_4[chw_stories$edu_5 ==4] = 3
##Factor stuff for reference, will need to be rerun after grouping
chw_stories$edu_5 <- factor(chw_stories$edu_5,
                           levels = c(0,1,2,3,4),
                           labels = c("<MS","<HS","HS/GED","Some College","College+"))
chw_stories$edu_4 <- factor(chw_stories$edu_4,
                           levels = c(0,1,2,3),
                           labels = c("<HS","HS/GED","Some College","College+"))
chw_stories$gender <- factor(chw_stories$gender,
                             levels = c(1,2),
                             labels = c("Male","Female"))
chw_stories$age_4 <- factor(chw_stories$age_4,
                             levels = c(1,2,3,4),
                             labels = c("18-24","25-44","45-64","65+"))
chw_stories$race <- factor(chw_stories$race,
                            levels = c(1,2,3,4,5,6),
                            labels = c("White","Black","Asian","Latinx","MENA","Other"))
chw_stories$needs_access_transportation <- factor(chw_stories$needs_access_transportation,
                            levels = c(1,2),
                            labels = c("Yes","No/NA")) 
chw_stories$familial_social_support <- factor(chw_stories$familial_social_support,
                            levels = c(1,2),
                            labels = c("Available","Unavailable"))
chw_stories$housing_3 <- factor(chw_stories$housing_3,
                            levels = c(1,2,3),
                            labels = c("Stable/Healthy","Unstable/Unhealthy","Homeless"))
chw_stories$home_unhealthy <- factor(chw_stories$home_unhealthy,
                            levels = c(1,2),
                            labels = c("No", "Yes"))
chw_stories$employ_7 <- factor(chw_stories$employ_7,
                            levels = c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7),
                            labels = c("Full time","Part time","Looking","Unable to work","Not Looking","Student","Retired"))
chw_stories$unfair_housing <- factor(chw_stories$unfair_housing,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No/NA"))
chw_stories$access_transportation <- factor(chw_stories$access_transportation,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No"))
chw_stories$interpersonal_violence <- factor(chw_stories$interpersonal_violence,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No/NA"))
chw_stories$school_violence <- factor(chw_stories$school_violence,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No/NA"))
chw_stories$health_insurance <- factor(chw_stories$health_insurance,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No"))
chw_stories$access_medication <- factor(chw_stories$access_medication,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No"))
chw_stories$health_physical_condition <- factor(chw_stories$health_physical_condition,
                                     levels = c(1,2,3),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No/NA", "No Access to Doctor"))
chw_stories$health_edu_access <- factor(chw_stories$health_edu_access,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Needed", "NA"))
chw_stories$needs_access_healthyfood <- factor(chw_stories$needs_access_healthyfood,
                                     levels = c(1,2),
                                     labels = c("Yes", "No/NA"))

Participant Characteristics Plot

I plot the summary table data with ggplot2.

#Gender
df_Gender <- df_demo  %>% slice(2:3)
colnames(df_Gender) = c("Gender", "Frequency", "Percent")
df_Gender$Percent <- as.numeric(as.character(df_Gender$Percent))
df_Gender$Gender <- factor(df_Gender$Gender, 
                               levels = c("Male", "Female"))

Gender_plot <- ggplot(data=df_Gender, aes(x=Gender, y=Percent, fill=Gender)) +
    guides(fill=FALSE) +
   scale_fill_viridis(discrete=TRUE,option="D",direction = 1) +
    scale_color_viridis(discrete=TRUE,option="D",direction = 1) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100)) +
   # coord_flip() +
   geom_bar(stat="identity", width = 0.5) +
geom_text(aes(label=Percent), nudge_y = 8, size=7) +
          xlab("") + 
  ylab("%") +
    theme_ipsum_rc(axis_text_size = 14,plot_title_size = 35) +
  ggtitle("Gender")
  
ggsave('Gender_plot.png',Gender_plot, width = 7.5, height = 5, units = "in")

    geom_text(aes(label=Percent), nudge_y = 3, size=15) +
  xlab("") +
  theme_ipsum_rc(axis_text_size = 40,axis_title_size = 30, plot_title_size = 50) +
  ggtitle("Problems & Barriers Reported")
  
ggsave('barriers_plot.png',barriers_plot, width = 25, height = 10, units = "in")

Exploratory Alluvial Diagrams

Now, I will explore two alluvial diagrams using the ggalluvial package. This will show us the combination of frequencies between selected variables. These combinations of frequencies could also be thought of as different pathways that individuals might take between these variables.

The beautiful thing about utilizing alluvial diagrams is that we are able to ask different questions by viewing the data from various perspectives. If you would like to suggest a subset or pathway to explore, feel free to send an inquiry and we can take a look!

I prepare the data, run the alluvial, and save the plot in one chunk. Preparing the data involves transforming it into tabular format so that every combination of variables is represented by a row with a frequency column. Please see Alluvial Plots in ggplot2 for more details (Brunson, 2020).

The method I employ is based around asking specific questions. Given the limitations of this data, these interpretations are exploratory in nature.

The first exploratory question is:

  • Among those in the work force (n=58; Full time, Part time, Unemployed-looking), what is the relationship between education, social/familial support, employment, and housing outcomes?

The second exploratory question is:

  • Among those with a physical health condition and medication access data (n=36), what is the relationship between education, insurance, transportation, and medication access?

These questions are being asked in reflection to the problems and barriers reported by the group that were observed in the manual coding process, as well as the descriptive frequencies and visualizations.

Housing Alluvial

#select variables of interest
house_2 <- chw_stories %>% select(edu_4, familial_social_support, employ_7, housing_3)

#Omit mising from outcome
house_2 <- house_2 %>% drop_na(housing_3)
house_2 <- house_2 %>% filter(employ_7 == "Full time" | employ_7 == "Part time" | employ_7 == "Looking")
house_2 <- house_2 %>% drop_na(edu_4)
house_2 <- house_2 %>% drop_na(familial_social_support)

#calculate combinations into tabular format
input_names = names(house_2)
house_2_prep <- house_2 %>% 
  count_(input_names) %>% 
  unite_("ComboVar",input_names,sep=",",)

#split columns in tabular format
house_2_alluvia <- house_2_prep %>% separate(ComboVar,
                        c("edu_4","familial_social_support","employ_7","housing_3"),
                          sep = ",")
##fix column headers
colnames(house_2_alluvia) = c("Education","Support","Employment","Housing","Freq")

## Order values

house_2_alluvia$Education <- factor(house_2_alluvia$Education, 
                               levels = c("College+", "Some College", "HS/GED", "<HS","NA"))

house_2_alluvia$Support <- factor(house_2_alluvia$Support, 
                               levels = c("Available", "Unavailable", "NA"))

house_2_alluvia$Employment <- factor(house_2_alluvia$Employment, 
                               levels = c("Full time", "Part time", "Looking"))

house_2_alluvia$Housing <- factor(house_2_alluvia$Housing, 
                               levels = c("Stable/Healthy", "Unstable/Unhealthy", "Homeless"))

#plot
alluvia_housing_2_plot <- ggplot(as.data.frame(house_2_alluvia),
       aes(y = Freq, 
           axis1 = Education, axis2 = Employment, axis3 = Support, axis4 = Housing)) +
      guides(fill=FALSE) +
  geom_alluvium(aes(fill = Housing), width = 1/8) +
  geom_stratum(width = 1/16, fill = "black", color = "white") +
  geom_label(stat = "stratum", aes(label = after_stat(stratum)), size = 9) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("Education", "Employment", "Support", "Housing"), expand = c(.05, .05)) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete=TRUE,option="D",direction = 1) +
  scale_color_viridis(discrete=TRUE,option="D",direction = 1) +
  theme_ipsum_rc(axis_text_size = 40,axis_title_size = 30, plot_title_size = 50) +
  ggtitle("Housing Pathways")

ggsave('alluvia_housing_2_plot.png',alluvia_housing_2_plot, width = 25, height = 10, units = "in")

Figure 3: Housing Alluvial

Frequencies for each housing outcome:

##   house_2$housing_3  n    percent
##      Stable/Healthy 33 0.56896552
##  Unstable/Unhealthy 23 0.39655172
##            Homeless  2 0.03448276

We can see proportions of the final outcome at every variable/bar. Different trends or pathways can be observed by following groups left to right.

  • People with less than high school and some college education are the only categories that reported being homeless.

  • No one employed full time is homeless, but both people looking for work and employed part time are.

  • There are only two individuals who are homeless in this subset. This may be influenced by a trend noticed in the qualitative coding process where people without employment or substantial income but with available support report unstable housing (e.g., staying with friends and family). It is possible that some respondents with available support who reported unstable/unhealthy housing might have increased risk of homelessness without familial or social support.

Figure 4: Medication Access Alluvial

Frequencies for each medication outcome:

##  med_2$access_medication  n percent
##                      Yes  9    0.25
##                       No 27    0.75

  • The <HS and college+ education groups are the only ones with no access to medication. The HS/GED and some college groups report access in this sample.

  • People with insurance have a higher proportion of access to medication.

  • No one in this alluvials subset reported yes to having transportation access. This data was either unavailable or people reported no.

  • The proportion of the group with missing transportation data that have access to medication is larger than the group that reported transportation as a barrier.

Conclusion

In summary, alluvial diagrams are a powerful method for visualizing categorical data to understand the relationships between variables in an exploratory fashion. While there are sample size limitations to this data, future work will attempt to better identify specific and implementable interventions to serve this community.
